<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910327-0084</DOCNO><DOCID>910327-0084.</DOCID><HL>   Credit Ratings:   Ratings Covering Debt   Of 3 Tobacco Concerns   Are Affirmed by Sandamp;P</HL><DATE>03/27/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8</SO><CO>   RN AMB LTR MO</CO><IN>STOCK AND BOND RATINGS (RTG)BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)</IN><LP>   NEW YORK -- Standard andamp; Poor's Corp. affirmed the ratingson three tobacco companies' debt following the SupremeCourt's decision to consider a big liability issue forcigarette makers.   The court this week said it would consider whether healthwarnings on cigarette packages protect tobacco companies frompersonal injury lawsuits.</LP><TEXT>   The ratings agency confirmed the single-A-minus rating ofAmerican Brands Inc.'s senior debt and the A-2 rating on itscommercial paper; the double-A-minus rating of LorillardInc.'s senior debt, and the single-A rating on Philip MorrisCos. senior debt. RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp.'s double-Bsenior debt remains on CreditWatch, where it was placed March20 with positive implications.   Sandamp;P said that any potential credit impact of a courtruling against the tobacco companies is unlikely over thenext two to three years, because of the length of thelitigation process and because cases must be tried onindividual merits.</TEXT></DOC>